ce:section.ce:para:
The developed ratiometric fluorescence sensing system based on D@CDs/Cu2+ was systematically evaluated for its analytical performance in detecting ZOL. Under optimized experimental conditions, incremental concentrations of ZOL (10.0–90.0 nM) were introduced to the system, triggering a distinctive dual-signal response pattern (Fig. 3
                        A). The interaction between ZOL and the sensing platform resulted in a simultaneous enhancement of fluorescence emission at 578 nm and diminution at 370 nm, enabling reliable ratiometric detection. The quantitative relationship between the fluorescence response ratio (F578/F370) and ZOL concentration exhibited exceptional linearity throughout the investigated range (Fig. 3B), yielding the mathematical expression F578/F370 = 0.007CZOL + 0.199 with a high correlation coefficient (R2 = 0.9949). The method demonstrated remarkable sensitivity, achieving a detection limit of 2.15 nM. A critical comparison between previously reported methods and our novel approach for ZOL detection reveals several significant analytical advantages of the proposed dual-emission system (Table 1
                        ). Earlier fluorometric methods relied predominantly on single-wavelength emission carbon dots operating in the blue spectral region, which inherently poses challenges in complex biological matrices due to potential interference from native fluorophores and matrix effects. These limitations restricted their practical application primarily to spiked samples under controlled conditions, falling short of real-world analytical demands. In contrast, our innovative approach leverages the unique properties of dual-emission carbon dots, where the simultaneous enhancement at 578 nm and decrease at 370 nm enables robust ratiometric detection. This ratiometric strategy provides an internal reference signal that effectively compensates for environmental fluctuations and matrix effects, substantially improving the method's reliability in complex biological samples. The analytical performance is further enhanced by incorporating a selective solid-phase extraction procedure, which effectively isolates ZOL from potentially interfering substances in biological matrices. The method's exceptional sensitivity, achieving a detection limit of 2.15 nM, coupled with its demonstrated applicability in real serum samples from rats with induced renal dysfunction, represents a significant advancement in ZOL analysis. This comprehensive analytical solution not only overcomes the limitations of single-emission methods but also extends the practical utility to challenging biological samples, making it particularly valuable for monitoring ZOL levels in patients with compromised renal function where precise dosing is critical.
